Just to clarify... -A handsome group of impressionable young people spent the Thanksgiving weekend with us.  They were impressed with the appreciable myriad (according to their reckoning)  of art friends we've accrued on the old fb and ig (and previously on yt) social media and business pages. 
Well as much as I would be flattered if indeed my personal influence had as great a reach as the young people's imaginations had them convinced it does and,  as much as our pages are and have been purely content driven ( no paid or sponsored growth methods used) and,  as much as I  do consider us mostly to be true art friends,  there has not been any material benefits,  at least in the form of FREE stuff, sponsorships, requests to help promote products etc. that I have availed myself of. No, that kind of experience is the stuff of legends I'm afraid.  That is indeed rarefied air that is breathed by  few souls and,  God forbid,  you or I ever have to deal with the nasty kind of temptations that accompany fame and fortune at the level some dream about. 
Pretty much all we do,  you and I,  that is of any real value comes by dint of hard work,  trial and error and the investment of love, blood and magical luck. So, you see that I'm still in the Thanksgiving mode ( my very favorite holiday) and I do indeed give much thanks to the great and kind and good Creator of all things good, for you, my art friend and for every moment I'm able to appreciate you and the ability to keep painting with the nine good fingers I got left. #happyholidays

Beautiful,  affordable,  giftable art from the nine fingered artist formerly known as Paco. 
Ok, to be completely honest, it was only the last inch of my finger ( left thumb) that was found crawling around the shop floor by Eli...under its own miraculous power!  Five weeks out and my Mississippi River/ amphibian DNA seems to be kicking in.  There are signs of regrowth ( please let the nerves know it ) and,  as viewed on a recent post,  my guitar picking is as slow and methodical (if not melodic) as ever. - no worse forwear apparently.  So, aside from the percocet withdrawls and extra carrying on about my suffering in hopes to get some free sympathy,  nothing has really changed.  It is funny though how our first reaction to pain is to question "why me?". As if something we did wrong has karmatically come back to get us. Personally I do take these kind of painful little setbacks as a sort of correction.  I try to readjust my perspective and see if there's anything I'm missing on my journey to forever.  Those of us that have had the opportunity to glimpse the other side I think are maybe a bit more accountable.  Regardless,  we're all pilgrims and  we'd all probably do well to stand back and take stock from time to time.  The thicker skulls amongst us apparently need to chop off a finger to get our attention 🤪

Tittle: Folk Art Polar Bear Getting Ready for Christmas-  8x8 oil painting on cradled wood panel. 
Whenever my drawing looks a bit  cockeyed I  just call it folk art and it's all good.  That's what I get for depicting animals that I'm not too familiar with.  I  could blame it on the missing finger but I'm discovering there's not much I can't do without a left thumb tip.  Buttoning the right sleeve cuff and cracking eggs into the pan are practical activities that seem to give opposable thumbs bearers a real advantage in the world  of  animal achievements. Those are two things  in which no substitute fingers can fill in...and what separates man from beast. I  am becoming more and more convinced it is the ONLY thing that sets us apart.  Try it and you'll see what I'm talking about.

Large canvas oil painting under $200 ¡¡¡!!! Is that even a thing? Show me and I'll believe it when I see it. 
Clouds and moon on canvas...again.  Will anyone ever join me in my lonely heavensward vigil? Well, a few years ago,  while wallowing in cloud-depicting obscurity,  I was contacted by the coolest club you could ever be a part of.  The #cloudappreciationsociety ( yes, that one!) asked if one of my cloudscape paintings could be used for the cover art on Gavin Pretor-Pinney's next best-selling book. How did they find me? Resigned to my self- imposed cloud ogling exile, I  figured I was pretty much alone in my quest to  spend as much time as possible watching the sky. Of course I wasn't ignorant of the like minded, kindred spirits that also enjoy looking up- I even knew of the existence of the exclusive and venerable (secret?) society.  However, I never thought,  not in a million years,  that my little art blog featuring my humble #skypaintings would come to the attention of such admirable personages as my fellow sky watchers and writer of books on #cloudspotting .  I suppose I have painted quite a healthy little pile o' paintings in my day and a lot of them have made it onto walls both domestic and exotic so, I guess if you stick with something long enough even the rascals amongst us will get the odd nod or wink of approval.  I'm not bragging here folks, just wanted to let you know how cool it is to share our #artpicture with each other ...with one eye in the clouds and the other on that forever elusive #masterpiece . The long and winding road/line of humans snaked out and around the solitary building that housed the immigration officers and their  stamp of approval. I needed a visa and I needed a  permit to drive the 500 miles of bad roads heading way south of my nordic origins. Traveling the uncharted hinterlands is not for the faint of heart. Navigating the borderlands during a holiday season is nothing short of loco. Waiting in line is something most hinterland dwellers are good at and it's something to expect, if not dread, when you undertake to travel in said hinterlands.  Well,  the long line that faced us with what was to be the first (and longest) of many to be encountered during our spearhead voyage did not yield a promising outlook  for this otherwise intrepid traveler. Waiting in lines is not my forte and  for all the many a third-world hour I have spent languishing in long lines you might think I'd have learned something.   Well,  learn something I did.  I  won't go into details but suffice it to say that the three hours wait was almost miraculously reduced to mere  minutes by a handshake, a nod and a wink and...some choice shekels placed in the correct palm. 

In the same way some of these holiday paintings can be displayed in the home,  office or gallery of your choice.

Trauma mucho?  I guess we all go through our own versions of it. I  listened to a podcast recently.  The dude said every once in a while he needed to strip down and wander  off into the deepest darkest jungle and confront death at spear, fang or claw point just to get a little perspective.  Apparently the life of ease ( he lamented his easy , "educated" life ) breeds some weird stuff.  A lot of folks appear to need to pursue adventure or fear or come up with something to either feel guilty about or to make others feel guilty about just to satisfy their own ... conscience(?). My answer to a restive heart? ( besides #arttherapy ) 
Well,  I  have gone off into the deep dark jungle,  more than once, and I think I get what the dude was getting at. In fact I  think I've actually died a couple of times trying to get what that guy is getting at.(three times actually) However,  the kind of risk  he pursued is only  part of the equation. You wanna strip your life down to the bare naked essentials? Find real purpose? Only one thing is needed I believe to make yourself get down to the nitty-gritty and cut to the core of your meaningless little life and petty opinions ( I'm talking to myself here) - leave off your headlong,  headfirst dive into pragmatism/ pragmatic thinking and make TRUTH the object of your desire. Truth, the pursuit of it,  will peel away bs like nothing else and it will set you on a path of  purpose and  ignorant bliss that the ancients only dreamed about.  Unfortunately  most of us don't  have the moxie  to want to know the difference between the two but trust me, they are like night and day. They are NOT synonymous.  Pragmatism has co-opted every thought system and institution in this old world I fear... The ends DO NOT justified the means amigos.  The journey is the ends. So, always do good - volunteer, give away  art, serve food, sweep the floor for Carmen and put no designs on the ends/outcomes and you will be the better for it. Now, let me crawl off my box and scurry back into my familiar hole of anonymity.

Title: Tall Trees, Tall Lights 24x12 
The muted mercurial circle of light on the street corner served as a gathering beacon for mosquitoes, June bugs, night hawks and...vandals. Streetlights don't break easily. What I mean is that you can't just put the things out with a casual toss of any old smooth stone. No, you've got to really chuck something large and hard. Probably throw as hard as you can, straight up, many times. That's what it takes. Glancing blows hardly faze those things. You'll need to make a direct hit. First the outer glass cracks, breaks, begins to crumble and then rain. It takes two or three good hits. Half inch thick shards will fall on your head if you're not careful. Finally, after too many misses to count, a rock (or chunk of asphalt) makes it through to the chewy center and..."pop" it goes. The sparkling light shower is really something to behold, quite rewarding for all the effort.You only have a few moments to bathe in it's fugitive fusile glow. Sometimes a painting is like that old streetlight on the corner of 72nd and Riverdale road. They can be tenacious buggers. But once you get to the core, find the key, it all comes together in a luscious blast that the artist savors but for a moment and then ...runs away before someone calls the cops.

Just to refresh the memory banks...
This is the view I  have looking south-southeast from the studio.  I  have to remind myself cuz staring directly into the burning, molten  core of a white hot canvas 10 hours a day,  it's easy to forget that magical moments of mystery and mischief are just outside the door. These mountains,  the Santa Catalinas,  are our home. They are also home to collared peccaries, lions, black bears, rattlers, buzzards and the ruins of ancient civilizations. Fire, water, blood and smoke pour and swirl and effervesce off her ragged and rugged slopes in an endless and almost merciless hypnotic cycle that portends things of the most supernatural nature. Snow capped and formidable, they are a "sky island" redoubt of rocky promontories, jagged ridges, bald faces and improbable precipices. These mountains are slashed and sprinkled with micro-rivulets and springs of coolness that belie the hella heat and death that lay scalding and scorching and burning and baking within a finger nail's scratch of the sun-exposed crust/ scaled veneer. Eternal portals, lay lines and dwarvish doors and tunnels pierce and penetrate her chewy subtext and if anyone ever invites you to hike up her backside,  you better think twice. But do it! She's as beautiful as she is wicked!

Update/final 24x12 inches oil painting on stretched canvas.  It has a new name:
Cooper'sHawk Moon 

I  freed this little Coopers Hawk yesterday right before I put the finishing touches on the canvas.  He was stuck inside the chicken run, caught in a quantum entanglement. It looks like he must have blasted through the aviary anti hawk forcefield while in a high powered dive.  He probably  started his vertical stoop at about one hundred feet and reached as many miles per hour before he broke the sound and net barrier.  Anyways,  I'm sure he did this to show his disdain for Paco's art as well as his chickens. He was stuck inside with 20 or so multi-colored big fat hens and one Bantam rooster.  The chickens were  laughing at him and actually jeered ( in their own inimitable way) as he was delicately and carefully extricated from the netting and set free...to live and stoop another day - none the worse for wear, I'm (semi) happy to report. Was Mr Cooper's little life lesson a metaphor for artists? I  believe so...on many levels. Artist Quote & Title: I always knew that I was a different sort of bird. For, if  "most men lead lives of quiet desperation" as I read in Thoreau's book about a hundred or so years after he wrote it,  I  was quite the opposite.  In fact,  the loud and adventurous youth of my yesteryear,  albeit with plenty of reason for "quiet desperation " focused more on the lines following the now famous quote. And console myself I did indeed do. You see, the bravery of muskrats and minks is nothing to scoff at.  The little brown-furred creatures with their white and yellow fangs and incisors,  and long, shiny black, guard hairs brought much philosophical light to the otherwise hopeless and barren backdrop of the life of the artist formerly known as Paco ... previously known as Billy. Yes, he tried to wax philosophical about his semi-fatherless youth and the broken dreams of an unexpected broken family but, the melancholy and despair brought on by the death of close kin only served to anneal his rugged heart against the vagaries and vicissitudes of this life of weary woe. Yes, the apparent ignoble and lowly muskrat with their anemic vegan diet of weeds and tubers inspired the nascent artist within and set him on a path of life-long joy that's found only in the journey...and guitars, and time-travel and grave-robbing and oil painting!  Full quote below- " The mass if men lead lives of quiet desperation. What is called resignation is confirmed desperation. From the desperate city you go into the desperate country, and have to console yourself with the bravery of minks and muskrats." - Henry David Thoreau

I  grew up near farming lands.  My bestest buddy Randy was a dairy farmer. He was as near and dear to me in my most formative years as his holsteins were to him. My friend Prince.
It was1979 or 1980. I'm not sure which.  My high school band mates and I were playing a low-keyed gig somewhere near Edina, Minnesota if memory banks serve their purpose. Around 10 o'clock  someone said something about going to a neighbor's house to meet a "real cool black guy who has a studio in his house...his name is Prince".  No one had ever heard of Prince, but the prospect of blowing my harp in a real recording studio was  intriguing. I asked if Prince played the blues.  "No", they said, "he's into funk and disco".  To which I said "squaresville daddy-o, I don't dig that scene".  My buddies all left me to go hang out with Prince. For the rest of the night I was alone with my harmonicas and ...the blues.  They all had a great time.  Now, instead of what might have been, I paint pictures like the ones here. On Graves & Grave Robbing
From the very beginning of my expeditionary ramblings I’ve had a desire, small at first, but always niggling, to discover and unearth an ancient grave. Nothing morbid mind you. It’s just that I figure, once they’re gone well, they’re gone. No sense fussing over the sensibilities of someone who’s not there. Right? Nevertheless, with due respect for the living I’ve refrained from overt body snatching and even though I’ve developed a keen interest in digging up stuff that’s not mine, I’ve held back…for the most part. You see, I’m really not afraid of ghosts and the like and since I swore off curses and cursing (for the most part) a long time ago I always assumed that I would be a good candidate for entering the ancient tomb and bringing to light the treasures long hid with the mummy. The exposed above-ground sepulcher s common in the little mountain village that was my haunt for a many years were tempting. There I found myself torn between the potential for the proverbial hot tamales hitting the fan (If I got caught) and, the easy pickins’ these weathered adobe / brick ruins offered. I did broach the subject a time or two with some native confidants and was met with withering stares and disbelief. So, this desire was put on the back burner, until...

"Biography of a future time traveler. 
I'm living as though I've already traveled through time.    I'm telling my story as one who has  indeed not only time- traveled but as one who is fairly expert at it. Of course you can only go forward in time. The  past has already been and, short of the odd dickensian dream-sequence, the glimpses and hazy viniettes afforded us humans, of the past, are just that- hazy and efemeral in every respect.  You can't really go there,  (the past) . You can't touch it, you can not change it but you can go forward and you can come back... fast!    So as not to get too far into the weeds with all the technicalness of " time flight ",  as I've come to call it,  let me just say that it is possible( I've done it many times... by the reading of this story) and,  like many fictitious accounts of time travel it is mostly enjoyable,  interesting,  profitable and... dangerous.  It does not occur without its problems. The most immediate and the most unavoidable of which is a sea sickness that lasts for days that no amount of pre-flight dramamine can mitigate- something about the acceleration and fragmentation of atoms in the time space vacuum created by time flight itself tends to be very unsettling to organic structures/ living things.  However, whatever the problems encountered  they are completely overshadowed by the enormous benefits ..."

The year was 1998. We were living in a little hilltop village 🎵🎼... called 🔥El Infierno 🔥 smack dab in the middle of the burning heart of Mexico.  Between rattlesnakes,  buzzards and chiltepin peppers 🌶  I set up a still life as identical as possible to a painting I saw in an art book I had.  I'm pretty sure it was called Problem Solving for Oil Painters by Greg Kreutz. Remarkably the tulips, dark vase and plums were easy to come by. Once I had gathered together this most improbable collection of objects ( for living below sea level and wearing  spurs on my boots)  I set myself to replicate the painting I saw in that book .  We still have the little Christmas tin but the painting was painted over I think- repurposed into another work that's long since been lost to the ravages and dust of  yesteryear. I  came upon an old paper photograph of this the other day and it brought to me a melancholic  añoranza ...our niños were little and everyday was an adventure and lesson in survival...dodging bullets, dancing the fandango, catching sharks and ...oil painting!

From the blog archives...
Osa Johnson wrote a book called " I Married Adventure."  She and her husband Martin were the first to document with film the native,  aboriginal peoples and wildlife of Africa and the tropical islands of Malaysia (in the 1920's).  It was recommended to me by a well-meaning fellow who, by force of zeal, was submitted to my  compelling description of the writings of America's most adventurous and noble president, Teddy Roosevelt. The flumsy (clumsy and fumbling) anecdotes that comprise the "adventures" of this couple serve only to throw in stark relief the contrast between the real deal and the fake. It's not always easy to detect the fake, but when you come upon the real, everything else fades to the background (where it belongs).   Had my book recommender friend ever read Mr. Roosevelt he would have clapped a hand over his mouth before a word ever escaped his gaping verb-hole and simply nodded for me to carry on while secretly shaming himself for even thinking his little novel should be mentioned in the company and light of the true standard-bearer of adventure.   I did, however, listen to his word-in-edgewise and even abased myself to read his book thus, the knowledge I gained to share this with you.
There are a few areas where I think this applies. Politics of course and probably because almost all  politicians seem to equivocate (ignoble trait) when it's convenient; very hard to tell if they're fake.  Art is another area where, if you have access to the real good stuff everything else appears to be student-grade. Honestly, most of us "painters" never develop the eye of the real artist (I include myself here) but, at the very least we can have as our standard the very best.

Although we do live on a small  homestead that borders an Arizona streambed... it is a dry river! We live in a desert. The measure of a man...is how (if)he makes his bed when his wife is away. No, I'm not going off and recommending you read 12 Steps to Manhoodedness & Life by Jordin Patterson (though, Lord knows, most of us desperately need to !)  Believe it or not, I do actually make my own bed when the cat's away (figurative cat= Carmen) - albeit a bit wrinkly and crinkly.  No real props to me but I am fully willing to accept the consequences that are the result of my own bed-making. Nurses corners?  What are those?  Bouncing a coin off the tightened sheets?  Hardly. Making sure the cat (literal cat= Ollie) is out from under the covers when the bedspread is pulled up...I don't really remember!?!?!  The point is, I do actually behave somewhat domesticated even when prying eyes are not around to spy on my liberty.  Carmelita had to go and check on her mom - doña Carmen- in ol' Mexico so I'm gonna be fending for myself the next few days. Eli and the Ollie should help with the dishes and I'll pretty much be left to my own designs for most of the time.  How will Paco fair without his handler you ask? Well,  I  believe that a fellow ought to live his life in a such a way that the quixotic artist within will have nothing to be ashamed of when the ghosts of Christmas' past come calling...and so the beautifully wrapped 🎁 under the tree will contain the companion T-shirt you've been wanting (the one that says..."Because I'm Paco, That's why"  - I already have the one that says "Because I'm Bill, That's Why") ...also, while we're at it, a new flex-shaft dremel tool would be nice and maybe some Old Spice and a pair of argyle socks ...stocking stuffers?  DM me for a more ideas for my gift list OK? A beautiful holiday season poem from my good art friend Tim...and a great song of joy from Marissa,  Jessica and Paco. 

Art comes in many forms

The greatest was when the earth was born

A 3d masterpiece floating in space

With life giving happenstances on its face

The subject always changing as if it’s alive

A place where flora and fauna, live and can thrive

If you have lived here for just one single day

Then you’ve seen completely amazing transformations at play

With all the lifetimes navigating its endless wonders

From peaceful and silent to lighting and thunder

The spectrum of weather from tumultuous to serene

Hurricane winds, powerful, relentless, calm, still, and everything in-between

Great mountains rise and then fall back into the sea

Ever moving landmasses their reemergence the life giving key

Oceans currents churn the world’s water in a constant motion

Scenes of new life and death, touching every emotion

Spectacular colors at sunset painted across entire ever changing skies

Landscapes reborn from rain, a new day comes with the sunrise

Seasons demonstrating the time on the clock

New scenes painted each day on this life giving rock

How be it to have such a precious work of art

Was there ever a beginning or was there never a start

Could Its creator be supernatural

Or could it just be, ---super natural

Yours is the answer in which you believe

I’m just thankful for all the marvels and beauty we see

A canvas of molten rock and clay

The paint, all of the new wonders we see each day

Tim 12/7/23,
